				<img BORDER="0" ALT="Edit/Delete" src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/edit.gif"></a>
		
				<font face="verdana" size="3"><a name="5">Kelly Flock Interview</a></font><br>
				<font face="verdana" size="2">
				<b><a href="mailto:xanthus@everlore.com">Xanthus</b></a>
				[5/8/2001-2:27:33 PM]</font>
				&nbsp;<a href="Comments.asp?ID=426663"><font face="Verdana" size="2">Comments[1]</font></a>
				<p>
				<font face="verdana" size="2">Steve Fuller, otherwise known as Mennix sat down with SOE (Sony Online Entertainment) President and CEO Kelly Flock for an <a href="http://everquest.station.sony.com/hht/features/standards.jsp">interview</a> about how SOE set a new standard in online gaming world. Here is a small snipplet from the interview:
<blockquote>
<i>
<p>
<b>SF:</b> What role will the use of broadband technologies play in the next phase of MMOLGs?</p>
<p>
<b>KF:</b> The players will certainly have a better experience through broadband connections, and in fact over 25% of the EQ subscribers play from broadband. From the server side, it will still be in our interest to minimize the amount of data we're sending out, for a lot of reasons. Not the least being that the cost of bandwidth is still high, and in order to keep our subscription costs as low as possible we well need to be prudent about that amount of bandwidth we need to support our games. We will be able to send bigger and better updates more frequently to our players, so a lot of benefit of broadband will be in the ongoing support for the world, and not necessarily in the game play itself.</p>
</i>
</blockquote>
<p>
For those of you that dont know, Steve Fuller is the man behind the <a href="http://everquest.station.sony.com/hht/weekly.jsp">Dear Mennix Column</a> over at <a href="http://everquest.station.sony.com/hht/index.jsp">Harpy's Head Tavern</a> on the official EverQuest website.</font></p><p>&nbsp;</p>
		
